***

### **Q: Discuss Push-Pull power Amplifier. (Relates to Class B/AB) (5 Marks)**

**1. Introduction (1 Mark)**
A **Push-Pull Amplifier** is a type of power amplifier configuration that uses two active devices (transistors) operating 180° out of phase to deliver amplified power to a load. It is most commonly operated in **Class B** (transistors conduct for exactly 180°) or **Class AB** (transistors conduct for slightly more than 180° to prevent distortion) to achieve high efficiency.

**2. Circuit Description (1 Mark)**
*(Exam Tip: You can briefly draw or describe a transformer-coupled push-pull circuit)*
*   The circuit consists of an **Input Center-Tapped Transformer ($T_1$)** acting as a phase splitter, which provides two equal but opposite polarity signals to the bases of two identical transistors ($Q_1$ and $Q_2$).
*   The collectors of both transistors are connected to the ends of an **Output Center-Tapped Transformer ($T_2$)**, which recombines the signals and transfers the amplified power to the load ($R_L$). 

**3. Working Principle: The "Push" and "Pull" (1.5 Marks)**
The operation is divided into two alternating halves:
*   **The "Push" (Positive Half-Cycle):** The input phase-splitter applies a positive voltage to the base of $Q_1$ and a negative voltage to $Q_2$. Transistor **$Q_1$ turns ON** (forward-biased) and "pushes" current through the upper half of the output transformer. $Q_2$ remains OFF.
*   **The "Pull" (Negative Half-Cycle):** The polarities reverse. Transistor $Q_1$ turns OFF, and **$Q_2$ turns ON**. $Q_2$ now "pulls" current through the lower half of the output transformer. 
*   The output transformer ($T_2$) seamlessly stitches these two halves together to form a fully amplified 360° output sine wave.

**4. Key Advantages (1 Mark)**
*   **High Efficiency:** It provides a much higher theoretical efficiency (up to **78.5%**) compared to Class A amplifiers (which only offer 25-50%).
*   **Eliminates Even Harmonics:** The push-pull push configuration automatically cancels out all *even-order harmonic distortions* present in the circuit, resulting in a cleaner output signal.
*   **No Core Saturation:** Since the DC collector currents of $Q_1$ and $Q_2$ flow in opposite directions through the output transformer, their magnetic fluxes cancel each other out, preventing DC core saturation.

**5. Disadvantages / Limitations (0.5 Marks)**
*   **Crossover Distortion:** In pure Class B operation, the 0.7V cut-in voltage requirement of silicon transistors causes a "dead zone" at the zero-crossing. *(Note: This is fixed by upgrading it to a Class AB configuration).*
*   **Bulky & Expensive:** The requirement of two heavy center-tapped transformers makes the circuit bulky and costly.

***

**Exam Tip:** Be sure to emphasize the term **"Even Harmonic Cancellation"**. It is a unique and very important property of the Push-Pull configuration, and mentioning it instantly proves to the examiner that your concepts are clear!

