### **Q: Discuss Push-Pull power Amplifier. (5 Marks)**

**1. Introduction & Definition (1 Mark)**
A **Push-Pull Amplifier** is a type of power amplifier that contains a pair of active devices (transistors). It typically operates in a **Class B** configuration, meaning each transistor conducts for exactly one-half cycle (180°) of the input signal. It provides a much higher collector efficiency (near **70% to 78.5%**) compared to standard Class A amplifiers.

**2. Circuit Diagram Description (1.5 Marks)**
*(Exam Tip: Draw a standard transformer-coupled push-pull circuit)*
*   **Input Stage:** An AC input voltage is applied to a **Divider Transformer** (a step-up, center-tapped input transformer). The center tap is grounded. 
*   **Transistors:** It uses two identical transistors (e.g., two NPN transistors, $Q_1$ and $Q_2$). The ends of the secondary winding of the input transformer connect to their respective bases.
*   **Output Stage:** The collectors of both transistors connect to the primary winding of an **Output Transformer** (also center-tapped). The DC supply ($+V_{CC}$) is applied at this center tap. The secondary winding is connected to the load (like a loudspeaker).

**3. Working Principle (1.5 Marks)**
The input transformer acts as a phase splitter, providing two equal but 180° out-of-phase signals to the transistors.
*   **During the Positive Half-Cycle:** The upper terminal of the input transformer becomes positive, forward-biasing transistor **$Q_1$ (Turns ON)**. The lower terminal becomes negative, reverse-biasing **$Q_2$ (Turns OFF)**. $Q_1$ conducts and "pushes" current through the upper half of the output transformer. 
*   **During the Negative Half-Cycle:** The polarities reverse. The upper terminal becomes negative, turning **$Q_1$ OFF**. The lower terminal becomes positive, forward-biasing transistor **$Q_2$ (Turns ON)**. $Q_2$ conducts and "pulls" current through the lower half of the output transformer.
*   **Output:** The output center-tapped transformer recombines these two individual half-cycles, producing a complete, amplified 360° sinusoidal wave at the load.

**4. Advantages & Disadvantages (1 Mark)**
*   **Advantages:**
    *   Higher efficiency due to Class B operation.
    *   Provides distortion-free output by automatically cancelling out **even harmonic distortions**.
    *   No DC core saturation in the output transformer because the currents from the two transistors flow in opposite directions.
*   **Disadvantages:**
    *   Requires two identical center-tapped transformers, making the circuit **bulky, heavier, and expensive**.
    *   Requires two equal and opposite voltages at the input. 

***

**Exam Tip:** For a 5-mark question, specifically mention the terms **"Divider Transformer"** and **"Even Harmonic Cancellation"**. Highlighting that one transistor works at a time (Pushing and Pulling sequentially) will fetch you full marks instantly!

